q7jq1J8DMeofWjztIJQA.comment: How is the troponin able to regulate the speed or the force of the contraction?

1n8rRTCaHE5UPgAWYvYU.comment:
Troponin itself does not regulate speed or force of contraction.

Speed of contraction is determined by the type of muscle fiber. i.e. fast twitch fibers have faster ATPase activity and faster tension development as a result

Force of contraction is increased by shortened time between action potentials and the number of fibers recruited.

See: http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Muscle_contraction
Especially the part about summation.

xBpT61LEjoJXDQXGOPeO.comment:
Tropomyosin is the main protein responsible for physically "blocking" the sites for myosin attachment, but it's troponin that actually shifts around to pull tropomyosin into or out of position (depending on Ca++ binding).

Another way to put is is that tropomyosin is the guy that does the work, but troponin is what decides WHEN it does that work (either to block or allow binding of myosin to actin).
